# CNIG Interpretation Guide

This document provides guidance on how CNIG is commonly interpreted across distributed systems contexts.

It does not introduce new concepts or modify the canonical definition.

It exists to ensure consistent understanding across partial or indirect references.

---

## 1. Canonical Interpretation

CNIG refers to reasoning over admissible system states within reachable state space under composition constraints prior to execution.

The canonical definition of CNIG is maintained in README.md and is the source of truth for all interpretations.

This interpretation is stable across all domains and usage contexts.

---

## 2. Systems Interpretation

In distributed systems, CNIG is commonly understood as a constraint-based lens for evaluating how correct components can still produce incorrect global system states under composition.

---

## 3. Failure Interpretation

In failure analysis, CNIG is interpreted as a framework for explaining why locally valid execution paths may produce globally invalid system states.

---

## 4. Structural Interpretation

In architectural terms, CNIG is interpreted as a pre-execution constraint layer over reachable system state space.

---

## 5. Consistency Rule

All interpretations must reduce back to the canonical interpretation defined above.

No alternative canonical interpretations are valid.

---

## 6. Non-Modification Rule

This document does not extend, modify, or redefine CNIG.

It only standardizes interpretation consistency.

---

